<section xml:id="section-assignment-week11">
  <title>Week 11 Assignment</title>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{3n!}{(n!)^3}
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{(-1)^n (n^3 + 2n +1)}{(n^2+1)}
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=2}^\infty \frac{\sin^2 \left( \frac{n\pi}{2} \right)
        \cos^2 \left( \frac{n\pi}{2} \right)}{n}
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence. (Use the ratio test. The
        challenge here is all about factorial algebra. Match up the
        various factorials and see how you can cancel terms to get a
        reasonable limit.) (6) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=1}^\infty \frac{n!(2n+1)!}{(2n)!(n+4)!}
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence. (4)
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=0}^\infty \frac{n^2}{\ln (n^2)} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Test this series for convergence (4). 
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=3}^\infty \frac{\ln n}{n^2} 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Assume that <m>a_n</m> and <m>b_n</m> are two sequences.
        Consider that the following series. (4)
      </p>
      <me>
        \sum_{n=1}^\infty a_n - b_n 
      </me>
      <p>
        How does the convergence of this series depend (if at all) on
        the convergence of these two series:
      </p>
      <md>
        <mrow>
          \amp \sum_{n=1}^\infty a_n \amp 
          \amp \sum_{n=1}^\infty b_n 
        </mrow>
      </md>
    </li>
  </ol>
</section>
